Git and GitHub using R

Who are you?



  • Lucy work with R and R studio to analyze data
  • Lucy use R-Projects
  • Lucy use RMarkdown to organize and document your work
  • Lucy have tried different ways of sharing your work.
  • She had heard about Git, and has the feeling that it might help. But she is not sure where to start.
  • She wants to understand how Git and GitHub works and wants to integrate this with RStudio.

Version control, what is that?



Git:

  • saves all the changes that were done on the code,
  • allows to access the history of changes and to go back to older versions of the code,
  • allows to compare changes between different versions,
  • helps with teamwork. Tracks who did each change,
  • recover files that were deleted.

Working Locally

Working Locally: Basic commands



git add

  • Description: Adds file to staging area.

    • Prepares the content staged for the next commit.
    • Starts saving versions and changes of the file.

  • Options:

    • git add file-path
    • git add -all



git commit

  • Description: Saves changes into local repository-

    • Saves a version of the file.
    • Sends from staging area to local repositoriy.
    • Good practice: Only one/few tasks per commit.
    • Good practice: Write meaninfull commit messages.

  • Options:

    • git commit -m “First commit”

Working remotely

Working remotely: Basic commands



git pull

  • Description: Updates local repository from remote repository

    • Downloada changes from the remote repository to local repository.
    • A warning will appear if there is a conflict.

  • Options:

    • git pull remote



git push

  • Description: Send changes from local repository to remote repository.

    • A warning will appear if I do not have the latest version of the repository.
    • To avoid this, pull before pushing.
    • A warning will appear if there is there an incompatibility.

  • Options:

    • git push
